data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — these APIs work identically on .NET 8. It will compile and run correctly as-is.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort): You could replace the manual threading with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
}
```

Or with tasks + cancellation support:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken token = default)
{
    var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, token), token));
    await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
}
```

These are **quality-of-life improvements**, not migration requirements.
